 Introduction:
In this tutorial, we will show you how to build a simple and effective homemade GPS tracker using Arduino and GPS module. This device is capable of tracking the location of any object within 5-10 meters precision.
2. Hardware Requirements:
To make your own GPS tracker, you will need following hardware components:

- Arduino Board (Any version)
- GPS Module (UBlox NEO6M or similar)
- Breadboard
- Jumper wires
- Power source (Battery or USB cable)

3. Software Requirements:

* You will also need to install the necessary software on your computer for programming and monitoring the GPS tracker.
* Download and install Arduino IDE (Integrated Development Environment) from official website.
4. Setting up the Hardware:
Connect the GPS module with the Arduino board using jumper wires as follows:
GPS Module -> Breadboard
Arduino Board -> Breadboard

1. Connect VCC pin of GPS module to 5V pin on Arduino board
2. Connect GND pin of GPS module to GND pin on Arduino board
3. Connect TX pin of GPS module to RX pin on Arduino board (In most cases it's digital pin 0)
4. Connect RX pin of GPS module to TX pin on Arduino board

Note: Make sure that the power source is properly connected and the device is powered on.

5. Writing Code:
Open the Arduino IDE and create a new project. Copy-paste the following code into your sketch:
```cpp
#include <TinyGPS.h>
#include <SoftwareSerial.h>

TinyGPS gps;
SoftwareSerial ss(0, 1);

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600);
  ss.begin(4800);
}

void loop() {
  while (ss.available() > 0) {
    char c = ss.read();
    gps.encode(c);
  }

  if (gps.location.isValid()) {
    Serial.print("Latitude: ");
    Serial.println(gps.location.lat(), 6);
    Serial.print("Longitude: ");
    Serial.println(gps.location.lng(), 6);
  }
}
```
This code will read the GPS data and print it to the serial monitor. You can adjust the serial baud rate according to your device.

6. Monitoring:
Open the serial monitor in Arduino IDE, set the baud rate to 9600 and click on "Connect". The GPS tracker will start sending location data to the serial monitor. You can use this data for tracking purposes.
7. Powering On:
Once you have completed setting up the hardware and written the code, power on the device using a battery or USB cable.

Note: Please be aware that the accuracy of the GPS tracker may vary depending on the environment and the number of satellites available.

8. Surveillance Tool:
Using this homemade GPS tracker as a surveillance tool can help track the location of people, vehicles, or objects within your desired range. You can also use it for tracking purposes such as monitoring pets, children, or employees.
9. Conclusion:
This is a basic tutorial on how to build a simple GPS tracker using Arduino and GPS module. With some modifications and additional hardware components, you can enhance the functionality of this device.

Remember that the accuracy of the GPS tracker may vary depending on several factors such as satellite availability, signal strength, and environmental conditions.
